n&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ). But this latest=
 case hinges on New York=E2=80=99s narrow version of likeness protection, w=
hich is limited to advertisement and trade within the state and within a sm=
all window of time, too. New York courts haven=E2=80=99t been particularly =
eager to expand this ambit. (See, for example, when Lindsay Lohan saw a Gra=
nd Theft Auto V character that looked and sounded like her and
sued ( http://business.cch.com/ipld/LohanTakeTwoInteractiveSoftware20180328=
=2Epdf?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing=
%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F3%2F24%29&u=
tm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F3%2F24%29&utm_medi=
um=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ).=
) Interestingly, upon the early emergence of deepfakes, the New York state =
legislature amended the law in 2021 and gave the heirs of dead people the a=
bility to control digital replicas, but that doesn=E2=80=99t look to be par=
ticularly helpful for living actors like Lehrman.

More promising is Lehrman=E2=80=99s assertions under the Lanham Act, a fede=
ral law aimed at protecting brands by guarding against consumer confusion a=
bout the source of a product or service. Lovo points out that Lehrman doesn=
=E2=80=99t own a trademark and doubts whether a voice alone can be protecte=
d under federal law. However, as long as something is distinctive enough to=
 potentially have secondary meaning, there
doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be any good legal reason why a voice couldn=E2=80=
=99t be trademarked. That said, such a voice would have better chances if i=
t were undeniably distinct, =C3=A0 la James Earl Jones or Christopher Walke=
n. Indeed, in the past, corporations have attempted to protect sounds. Thin=
k, for instance, of the MGM lion=E2=80=99s roar.

The tougher question is whether Lehrman can tie the alleged deception to lo=
ss. The declarations from Friedlander and Lewis may bolster his claims of f=
alse advertising and unfair competition, but Lovo noted that Lehrman hasn=
=E2=80=99t claimed that he=E2=80=99s actually lost work due to his A.I. dop=
pelg=C3=A4nger. Is it plausible that his voice carries enough recognition i=
n the $2 billion voiceover industry that the existence of =E2=80=9CKyle Sno=
w=E2=80=9D threatens to muscle him out? We=E2=80=99ll soon find out.

If Lerhman doesn=E2=80=99t succeed, the lesson may be that it=E2=80=99s dif=
ficult to apply old laws to new technology. After all, it=E2=80=99s hard to
protect something as intangible as a voice=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s not exactly=
 a physical asset, nor does it fit neatly in the old intellectual property =
paradigm. One can make a recording of a voice, and protect that recording, =
but only under certain circumstances. Alas, without policy changes, actors =
like Lehrman may have to play whack-a-mole on A.I. replication. They=E2=80=
=99ll scrutinize old contracts to guard against unauthorized use of old per=
formances and hope for changes that will create a more favorable legal envi=
ronment.

Could that environment change? Well, in New York, lawmakers unanimously pas=
sed a bill in the wake of Johansson=E2=80=99s dustup that requires clear co=
ntracts for the creation and use of digital replicas, nullifying any agreem=
ent for someone=E2=80=99s voice or likeness=E2=80=94such as those buried in=
 the fine print of social media services=E2=80=94that doesn=E2=80=99t speci=
fy intended use and isn=E2=80=99t negotiated by legal counsel. I=E2=80=99ve=
 heard the bill landed on Governor Kathy
Hochul=E2=80=99s desk over the weekend, and she has 10 days to sign it, or =
else it dies. Her office didn=E2=80=99t respond when I inquired after her i=
ntentions.

That=E2=80=99s all for today. I=E2=80=99ll see you on Thursday.
Matt

