e legislature amended the law in 2021 and gave the heirs of <i>dead people<=
/i> the ability to control digital replicas, but that doesn=E2=80=99t look =
to be particularly helpful for living actors like Lehrman.<br/><br/>More pr=
omising is Lehrman=E2=80=99s assertions under the Lanham Act, a federal law=
 aimed at protecting brands by guarding against consumer confusion about th=
e source of a product or service. Lovo points out that Lehrman doesn=E2=80=
=99t own a trademark and doubts whether a voice alone can be protected unde=
r federal law. However, as long as something is distinctive enough to poten=
tially have secondary meaning, there
doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be any good legal reason why a voice <i>couldn=E2=
=80=99t</i> be trademarked. That said, such a voice would have better chanc=
es if it were undeniably distinct, <i>=C3=A0 la</i> <b>James Earl Jones</b>=
 or <b>Christopher Walken</b>. Indeed, in the past, corporations have attem=
pted to protect sounds. Think, for instance, of the MGM lion=E2=80=99s roar=
=2E<br/><br/>The tougher question is wh=
ether Lehrman can tie the alleged dece=
ption to loss. The declarations from Friedlander and Lewis may bolster his =
claims of false advertising and unfair competition, but Lovo noted that Leh=
rman hasn=E2=80=99t claimed that he=E2=80=99s actually lost work due to his=
 A.I. doppelg=C3=A4nger. Is it plausible that his voice carries enough reco=
gnition in the $2 billion voiceover industry that the existence of =E2=80=
=9CKyle Snow=E2=80=9D threatens to muscle him out? We=E2=80=99ll soon find =
out. <br/><br/>If Lerhman doesn=E2=80=99t succeed, the lesson may be that i=
t=E2=80=99s difficult to apply old laws to new technology. After all, it=E2=
=80=99s hard to
protect something as intangible as a voice=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s not <i>exac=
tly</i> a physical asset, nor does it fit neatly in the old intellectual pr=
operty paradigm. One can make a recording of a voice, and protect <i>that <=
/i>recording, but only under certain circumstances. Alas, without policy ch=
anges, actors like Lehrman may have to play whack-a-mole on A.I. replicatio=
n. They=E2=80=99ll scrutinize old contracts to guard against unauthorized u=
se of old performances and hope for changes that will create a more favorab=
le legal environment.<br/><br/>Could that environment change? Well, in New =
York, lawmakers unanimously passed a bill in the wake of Johansson=E2=80=99=
s dustup that requires clear contracts for the creation and use of digital =
replicas, nullifying any agreement for someone=E2=80=99s voice or likeness=
=E2=80=94such as those buried in the fine print of social media services=E2=
=80=94that doesn=E2=80=99t specify intended use and isn=E2=80=99t negotiate=
d by legal counsel. I=E2=80=99ve heard the bill landed on Governor <b>Kathy
Hochul</b>=E2=80=99s desk over the weekend, and she has 10 days to sign it,=
